  "output": "This is a Swift/SwiftUI app (not React), so I adapted the \"re-render\" analysis to SwiftUI's equivalent — `@Observable` view models and body-level recomputation. Here's the analysis with verified file:line findings.\n\n## 1. N+1 Query Patterns\n\n**`VoucherService.swift:1164-1175`** — loops one `SELECT` per account instead of batching:\n```swift\n// Current\nfor id in ids { accountRepo.findById(id) }\n\n// Fix — reuse the batching pattern AccountRepository already has for codes\nlet accounts = accountRepo.findByIds(ids)  // single WHERE id IN (...)\n```\n\n**`BOMService.swift:70-87`** — `validateBOMInput` re-instantiates `InventoryRepository` and queries per-component inside the loop instead of one `IN (...)` fetch for all component IDs.\n\n**`DashboardViewModel.swift:54-62`** — the biggest one: for each bank account, it runs a *full ledger report* (its own query + reconciliation check):\n```swift\n// Current\nfor bankAccount in accounts where bankAccount.isBankAccount {\n    report.ledger(accountId: bankAccount.id, ...)\n}\n\n// Fix — ReportRepository already has a batched method\nlet accountIds = accounts.filter(\\.isBankAccount).map(\\.id)\nlet totals = reportRepository.movementTotals(for: accountIds, ...)\n```\nThis also defeats `ReportCache` (see §3) since each account gets its own cache key.\n\n**`InvoicePDFService.swift:47-57`** fetches one inventory item per stock-movement line via `findItemById`, when line 31-32 in the *same file* shows the correct pattern (batch fetch + dictionary lookup) already used for accounts — just not applied to items:\n```swift\n// Apply the same pattern already used above for accounts\nlet items = Dictionary(uniqueKeysWithValues: inventoryRepo.findItems(ids: itemIds).map { ($0.id, $0) })\nlet lines = movements.map { items[$0.itemId] }\n```\n\n## 2. SwiftUI Re-render Equivalent\n\nGood news: view models use `@Observable` (fine-grained diffing), not `ObservableObject`/`@Published`, so blanket invalidation isn't an issue here. Two real recomputation problems though:\n\n**`VoucherEditViewModel.swift:244-258`** — `totalDebitPaise`, `totalCreditPaise`, and `isBalanced` each independently re-parse every line's amount string (`Currency.parseRupeeInput`) on every access. A view checking `isBalanced` then displaying `totalDebitPaise` parses all lines twice:\n```swift\n// Fix — parse once, cache alongside line mutation\nprivate var cachedTotals: (debit: Int, credit: Int)?\nvar totalDebitPaise: Int { computeTotalsIfNeeded().debit }\nvar isBalanced: Bool { let t = computeTotalsIfNeeded(); return t.debit == t.credit }\n```\n\n**`AuditViewModel.swift:64-66`** — `entityTypes` recomputes `Set(events.map{...}).sorted()` over up to 1000 events on every read instead of caching it when `reload()` runs.\n\n## 3. Caching Opportunities\n\n- `ReportCache` (`ReportService.swift:116-179`) still issues a `changeToken` COUNT/MAX query on every cache read just to validate freshness — reasonable, but note it's undermined by §1's DashboardViewModel N+1, since per-account keys mean caching doesn't collapse the redundant queries.\n- **Company `isInventoryEnabled` flag** is re-fetched from DB on nearly every inventory mutation in 4+ places (`InventoryOrderService.swift:114`, `InventoryOrderRepository.swift:116`, `BOMService.swift:56`, `ReportRepository+ComplianceReports.swift:233`) despite rarely changing — a good candidate for a short-TTL or invalidate-on-write cache similar to `AccountTreeCache`.\n\n## 4. Memory Leaks\n\nNotably clean. Every `Task`/`Task.detached` closure reviewed correctly uses `[weak self]` (Payroll/Accounts/Vouchers/Inventory view models, `AppEnvironment.swift`, `KeyboardBridge.swift`), delegates are `weak var`, and there's no `NotificationCenter.addObserver` or `Timer.scheduledTimer` anywhere in the app to leak. One minor nit:\n\n**`AccountTreeCache.swift:89`** — `ensureLoaded()` does `Task { await reload() }` capturing `self` strongly, inconsistent with `reload()` elsewhere in the same file. Not a true cycle (singleton-owned), but worth the same `[weak self]` treatment for consistency.\n\n## 5. Redundant Computations\n\n- `DateFormatters.swift` correctly uses `static let` everywhere — no antipattern found there.\n- Same root cause as §2: `VoucherEditViewModel`'s repeated `parseRupeeInput` calls, and `AccountTreeCache.swift:58-67`'s per-ledger `signedOpeningBalance` calls (one query per ledger instead of one batched query for all ledger IDs — same fix shape as the Dashboard N+1).\n\n## Priority order\n1. `DashboardViewModel.swift:54-62` — highest user-visible impact (dashboard load time scales with bank account count).\n2. `VoucherEditViewModel.swift:244-258` — hot path, runs on every voucher-entry keystroke.\n3. `AccountTreeCache.swift:58-67` and `InvoicePDFService.swift:47-57` — same batch-fetch fix pattern, low risk since the pattern already exists elsewhere in each file.\n4. Company-flag caching (§3) — lower urgency, cosmetic win.\n",
